    "153913362": {
      "title": "Consensus Planning: The Relevance of Communicative Planning Theory in Dutch Infrastructure Development",
      "abstract": "Introduction: background aim and scope objectives outline and some methodological remarks. Theoretical underpinnings: shifting grounds in planning theory three views on consensus planning a view based on collaboration and learning a view based on bargaining and negotiating a view based on will shaping and persuasion bringing the views into focus. Some relevant issues for consensus planning: an issue of co-operation an issue of democracy pragmatic issues application issues some concluding remarks. The setting - infrastructure development in the Netherlands: the Dutch planning system and planning culture Dutch infrastructure policy some examples some concluding remarks. Evaluating consensus planning - an overall picture of Dutch initiatives: local participatory traffic in two cities the \"infralab approach\" - collaboration for local and regional implementation three \"open planning processes\" in regional infrastructure development three cases of regional consensus planning national corporate consensus planning some concluding remarks and discussion. Evaluating consensus planning - an assessment based on complexity: complexity the evaluation framework an evaluation of opinions an evaluation of cases some concluding remarks and discussion. Evaluating consensus planning - the position of residents in two cases: hypotheses measuring consensus case one - Groningen Airport Eelde case two - Hanze railway route some concluding remarks. Evaluating consensus planning - some critical reflections. The essence of consensus planning."
    },
    "127410956": {
      "title": "Ethnocracy, Land and Identity Politics in Israel/Palestine",
      "abstract": "Preface PART I. SETTINGS 1. Introduction 2. The Ethnocratic Regime: The Politics of Seizing Contested Territory PART II. ETHNOCRACY AND TERRITORY IN ISRAEL/PALESTINE 3. Zionist and Palestinian Nationalism: The Making of Territorial Identities 4. Debating Israeli Democracy 5. The Making of Ethnocracy in Israel/Palestine 6. The Spatial Foundation: the Israeli Land System PART III. ETHNOCRACY AND ITS PERIPHERIES: PALESTINIAN ARABS AND MIZRAHIM 7. Fractured Regionalism among Palestinian Arabs in Israel 8. Bedouin Arabs and Urban Ethnocracy in the Beer-Sheva Region 9. Mizrahi Identities in the Development Towns: The Making of a Third Space 10. Between Local and National: Mobilization in the Mizrahi Peripheries PART IV. LOOKING AHEAD 11. A Way Forward? The Planning of a Binational Capital in Jerusalem 12. Epilogue: A Demos for Israel/Palestine? Toward Phased Binationalism Notes Appendix References Index"
